
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `groups` baraye namayeshe grooh-haye karbari (user) estefade mishavad. Agar be soorate sade estefade shavad, grooh-haye karbar-e فعّal (fa'al - active) ra neshon midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `groups [username]` --> 👤 Namayesh grooh-haye karbare moshakhas.  Agar username dade nashavad, grooh-haye khode shoma ra neshon midahad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ groups

    🔹  Namayesh grooh-haye karbare فعّal (fa'al).

    $ groups ali

    🔹  Namayesh grooh-haye karbari ba name "ali".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ groups

    🔹  Agar kargardan bashid, liste grooh-hayei ke shoma ozv hastid ra neshon midahad. Masalan, "user admin wheel".

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `groups` command displays the groups a user belongs to.  If used without any arguments, it shows the groups of the current user.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `groups [username]` --> 👤 Display the groups a specific user belongs to. If no username is provided, it displays the groups of the current user.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ groups

    🔹  Display the groups of the current user.

    $ groups john

    🔹  Display the groups that the user "john" belongs to.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ groups

    🔹  If you are the current user, this will display a list of groups you are a member of. For example: "user admin wheel".

